segments.text: No, too, because we were only 11 grades.
Yeah.
And what, were you planning to go to college?
Oh, yeah.
All right.
I went there.
How did you get back and forth from here to Bryan High?
Driving a first one, I was driving a 28 Hummel sedan.
You drove the car yourself?
Yeah.
How many other kids drove their car to school?
I don't know.
Not that one.
And describe that Hupmobile.
A big old six-cylinder, four-door.
What color?
Blue.
And let's see, did it have a regular gear shift?
Yeah.
Cloth top or hard top?
That's what I thought.
The first one to come in with that hardtop would be a 37 Ford.
And did anybody ride with you, or did you go by yourself?
Well, I drove it all by myself for the first year.
And then, of course, my sister came on, too.
And so we drove together there.
The other sister came along.
Did anybody fuss at your parents or at you about your not going to A&M Consolidated?
No.
That didn't matter?
No problem at all.
Did you think that this was a better school than what you had gotten?
Yeah, quite a lot better.
Because they didn't have any manual training.
What about science courses?
What science courses did you take in high school?
Oh, I don't know what that lady was.
Her name was Klein.
She taught the science.
Did you have physics, biology, chemistry?
Well, it was just a general
Physics, I guess you would call it.
How much math?
We had all the math.
Were there some teachers you had that you now realize were very effective?
Yeah, particularly in English.
Who?
Whether I can remember that woman's name or not, but she's kind of a small woman.
She was tough.
She was tough.
Did you and your Bryan High School buddies ever do any pranks or tricks?
I never was around up there.
I was admitted to school because I went.
So you didn't get involved in any mischief?
No, I didn't get involved in any mischief.
Did you take part in any extracurricular activities?
Athletics, band?
No, see, I couldn't.
As I told you, I couldn't.
In my younger years, I couldn't do much or anything.
I can today.
And in those high school age years, what did you do in the summer?
We traveled.
Where?
Well, let's see, in 1928 we went to the ASHV, no, not the ASHV, the ASAE, ASAE society, on the train to Salt Lake City to, what's the one up in there?
Lake Tahoe.
We were there in 28.
My, my.
And Rockefeller was on the campus.
You can see that on the wind, yeah.
I was walking around there with a high collar, old and black.
What kind of personality did he seem to have?
We wouldn't even touch him.
The only thing about that place was that you couldn't swim.
What we did, we went out to the end of the pier, and you could read a damn newspaper down there, I don't know how far down.
The water was that clear?
That clear.
And all you had to do was, you just made up your mind, and you just,
You dove off into that thing, and then you turned around, and you climbed back that ladder as quick as you could.
Water was that cold?
Cold.
Deliciously cold.
All right, so where, and you went there.
Where else did you go in the summers?
We went to, that year we went to San Francisco, and we stayed there a while.
And then we got on a boat, a coastal steamer, and went to Portland.
And I was the only one that didn't get seasick out of all of us.
We got to Portland, and then we went toon the train from Portland, we went to Vancouver, and then across theacross the
an island out there.
And then we went back to Canadian Vancouver.
Well, first we went to Seattle and then we came back to Vancouver.
And we got on the Canadian Railway and went to Banff.
Have you been there?
No.
There's one more place you ought to go.
All right, other summers, where did you go?
Well, the next year we go at...
hub mobile to up to northern Minnesota two harbors on the north side of the up there and then we went to Canada one day came back with a bunch of Canadian blankets have you seen one of those
black, some of them black, some had some white ones with the stripe all the way across the top.
Those things, we were all, we had a hell of a time getting them back in there because we went across there to port, Huron I guess it is or some port and then we turned around almost too quick and
people that didn't like it.
Daddy talked them out of it.
So then we came back from that and we drove down to Redwood Falls, Minnesota.
My father had his brother, his uncle.
was living in Redwood Falls, Minnesota.
So you got to see some family.
Yeah, the old man, yeah.
And he had gone out there after my grandfather had died.
And they had tuberculosis, and they had Cromwell.
and they all split and so he had gone to out there in east western Minnesota and I remember that to this day.
Walked up there and there's a young man there and later we've seen him since and
He asked if it's Elmer.
Is Elmer here?
Told him who we were and he understood.
And so we went in there and the old man was raising honey.
What he loved to do was he had a bunch of honeybees and he was raising honey for
Oh, it's clover honey.
It's very sweet.
And so we walked in there and I can hear dad yell, I'm Will's boy.
Will's boy.
Just yelling at him.
Just yelling at him on top of his voice.
And finally the old man lightened up.
And he sure got it.

he come out of there and of course he was he was in his he was quite old i don't know how old he would have been but anyways he was just uh finally got warmed up to where dad who dad was and he was so glad to see him
We've kept up with those people.
See, that's what this is from.
All this stuff here.
Now, you traveled some in the summer.
Did you have summer jobs also?
Yeah, I had one.
What'd you do?
Well, Dad got it in 1934.
Dad got me a job at South Dakota State at Brookings for the whole summer.
What'd you do?
Well, they were...
They were interested in rammed earth construction, where you ram the earth and then you just let her stand.
And they had gone all over South Dakota and picked up all the different types of soil that they had there.
And they brought them back into this one.
And they had rammed them into this one great big old wall that they had up there that they built.

and uh so my job for that was that's what i really and i had to go out there and cut some of that dirt out of the way and where they had rods through there and stick and put concrete in there and seal it off so that hole that rod that went through that
He had two walls and they had these rods between them.
And they ran those things.
And they pulled in and they pulled the bolt out.
My job was to fix that up and get it ready to, they were going to struggle with it.
So that was one thing.
And then the other thing was that I just worked in the shops there.
And one morning, I was just sitting there, working around in there and straightening up things.
And this man came in through there.
And I've never seen a man so mad hot.
Oh, that man was hot.
He was really hot.
He says, come fix this damn tractor.
What had happened?
He'd gone out there and he was plowing that field that night before.
And he was plowing it with a Case cross-engine tractor.
Big old four-cylinder cross-engine.
It sticked crossways a little bit.
And so he had
just stopped out there, cut the engine off, and then he went, the next morning when he went out there, he just, well, I'll just go start it up again.
He was already fueled up and everything, I guess.
So he went out there and that crank was about
42 inches off the ground.
Very big old thing.
And so he had to stand out there and just crank it off his hand like that.
Well, some of their people there in the department had rebuilt the magneto on that tractor.
And they used ordinary shellac, not electrical shellac.
It wouldn't stand the heat.
So when he stopped that tractor and that heat got all over that mag, it stuck the rotor.
Between the mag and the rotor.
And when he was cranking it,
That impulse coupling that's on there, it's a wind-up arrangement on the spring, is what it went to.
And you just wind it, and you hear it click.
And you're supposed to fire that cylinder.
Well, it didn't until the last time.
And all of a sudden, it turned loose.
And it backfired on all four cylinders.
And he just went up from there, and about 30 yards out there in the field, I found two handprints and two knee prints.
Luckily, he had fallen on the soft earth again.
Now, was that job in 1934, was that while you were in college?
Yeah.
All right, let's back up.
Well, let me finish this.
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.
Well.
They were so poor.
I took it all apart, the tractor apart.
And they had used Model A spark plugs in them, which were too long.
And they were burning the tips off of them.
And so then I had to go.
They were so poor that I had to go to the president of the college.
And he had to go downtown and buy the...
Those spark plugs.
My goodness.
That's how poor they were up there.
And they had a whole dormitory full of women over there.
Right now, you mentioned poor.
Describe as fully as you can what depression, what the depression was like here at Texas A&M.
It was not bad.
You see, we got the Texas A&M people, the students and the professors were lucky.
See, Texas has a, we have a biannual appropriation, all right.
They had already made the appropriation.
They couldn't change it and so

what happened was that we dead had a pretty good salary there for quite a while and so then what happened was that they reduced it down in the next biennium and so the legislature made a tone that that the women and the
The daughters and the women of the professors could go here to school.
And there were 15 to 17 of them that did.
Now this is what, do you remember about when that was?
That would be in about 1933.
Did any of your sisters go?
Yes, both of them.
How were they treated?
Wonderful.
They got along real good.
They liked it?
They liked it.
They made some real good friends.
And the boys liked it, to have girls in the class?
I don't know.
I never had a girl in mine, but they did.
I know a bunch of them.
My sister, we were talking about it the other night, the other afternoon.
We were over at Luby's.
She was talking about it.
And she told me, and there was a, in the battalion, there was, right in the middle, there was a page in there with all her pictures.
And she's still got that battalion.
Now we're, and these were faculty daughters.
Faculty daughters or... Staff daughters.
Staff daughters.
But nobody, no other women were allowed.
But they did immediately, I think after that, they did let the, in summer school, let women go.
Now, were you all still living on the campus when the Depression hit?
No.
You had moved off.
We moved off, yes.

Dad he designed the house that we're living in and I remember him going we went all over this town there were several houses in here that he was looking at he wanted an overhang on that house it's three feet sticks out three feet this way flat and then of course you got the big roof on top of it but then
He designed it, and then he got a contractor.
And it was a whole turnkey job.
And see, that has a basement under it, too.
It had a furnace in it.
All of that was $75 million.
Do you remember what year that was?
That would be in 20, that would be in 24, because that's when we moved into it.
Okay, okay.
We moved into it on the 17th of November in 1924.
And so... December.
It would be December, not November.
All right, so you all are off campus, and the house is paid for and all, and the Depression hits.
But what about the effects of the Depression on the community here?
Oh, for any of them, not any.
What about in Bryan?
There was quite a lot of problems.
There were a lot of problems there.
We never were... We never did know too much about them.
They didn't have any people.
Well, the people just took care of other people, not doctors, for one thing.
The doctor never turned down a patient.
And then some of the Negro, some of the, one of them I know, they'd bring him up there to his house, and he would never take it in the house, but he'd, some Negro gets hurt, you know.
He'd just lay one of us on the driveway out there and patch him up.
The hospital was the old St. Joseph's north of the business district?
No, you know, Horton and Bryan?
No, it was that one that's on near the, I don't know what the name of that street is, goes west.
That's where it is.
It's not
I think they converted that into some sort of a... Retirement home.
Retirement home.
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, that one.
The building there.
Yeah.
But before that, it was down there near the courthouse.
You know, there's a building down there.
That's where they took my father.
He had his gallbladder out in 1932.
Now, here on the campus...
Were you faculty youngsters, were you eligible to go to the quack shack on the campus?
The hospital?
Oh, yeah.
Dr. Ellinger treated me.
Dr. Marsh treated me.
There were two of the Ellingers.
The old man.
Now he was a specialist in respiratory disease, principally pneumonia.
Now I've heard that Dr. Marsh delivered some children at the homes on the campus.
Well that was done all over the country.
Matter of fact,
My wife, I'm sure, was on there.
What they usually did, they went into the living room or the dining room.
You had a big old table.
And put the mother on the table?
Yeah.
They made a bed on top of the table and put her up there.
And that was the usual procedure.

One of the Cashion boys told me that Dr. Marsh and his wife had a commitment for dinner, and his mother went into labor, and so Dr. Marsh came over to their house and delivered him a little early so they could still make it to the dinner party.
Describe Dr. Marsh as you remember him.
I never did.
You didn't?
Dr. Ellinger.
But you think highly of him.
Dr. Ellinger?
Dr. Marsh was the one.
I was talking about Schultz.
His father told me that South Oakwood, he lived right there.
We knew each other because we backed up to his property.
He was down there.
He got hurt one day.
And somehow or another, I don't know what it was, something they had these, they made syrup.
You took sorghum and run it through a mill.
And then you took it in there and cooked it off.
Made molasses.
Well, you also made sorghum.
Well, sorghum molasses is what we called it.
Well, somehow or another, he got his arm into this machine.
And Dr. Morris was a young doctor then.
Just come to town.
I asked him about it here just not more than a couple years ago.
I asked him about the whole thing.
I said, I knew you were
you're injured, but I didn't know what it was at all.
But he said Dr. Marsh was in there.
And Dr. Marsh wouldn't, the doctors wanted to cut his arm off.
He was a regular doctor.
And Dr. Marsh went in there and he said, don't cut that man's arm off.
And he worked with it.
and worked with him until they got the bone back in the place.
And that man served in the Air Force.
Good.
Never requested it.
Oh, good.
So you understand what his...
So I always thought that he was a good man.
And there were others...
I don't know, they just seemed to, they had a good staff.
And another thing they had was, there was the nurses.
Were they good?
Excellent.
And one of them one day, they couldn't find a doctor, and this kid had come down with a,
a hell of a hurt in the right side, and she knew what was wrong.
She took all her help that she could find and some more, and she went in there and cut that appendix out all by herself.
My, my.
Who was that youngster?
Do you know?
I don't know the name of the youngster.
But it worked successfully.
Yeah, and I remember she was at the American Legion when I first went out there.
There were some tough women around.
Take on responsibility.
Another thing I always found, that the wife of an officer or men in service, I mean, where the woman had to do a lot of even shipping or taking care of things.
Sure.
They made the best people you could find, even if they were in the...
I kind of, well, they were supposed to work, but they didn't work.
In the 20s and early 30s, what did your mother do for pleasure?
What social groups did she... Oh, she went with...
civic clubs and the women around on the campus had a bunch of civic clubs that they worked with.
But in addition, my father realized that she was going to have some problems and so he got her interested in birds.
In what?
Birds.
And we have some birds in our, I've not found them yet, but he bought all the books that you could find on birds.
Oh, how marvelous.
Including the ottomans.
He had some of the big original models.
I think my sister's got it.
All right, a suggestion.
If the family is ever willing to part with any of those, please give them to this library so that your family's name would always be there.
If y'all ever want to pass them on outside the family, give them to the Texas A&M Library.
We've done that to a number of things.
Well, that's great, because... We discovered...
a book that the cemetery had out there, at the Bryan Cemetery, and it describes all, what the only problem is, it shouldn't be, I'm glad that colleges got it, because you could get sued over it.
